{"title_page": "V\u00edctor Bignon", "text_new": "{{short description|Chilean boxer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name           = V\u00edctor Bignon\n| full_name      = \n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| nationality    = Chilean\n| sport          = [[Boxing]]\n| birth_date     = \n| birth_place    = \n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n}}\n\n'''V\u00edctor Bignon''' was a Chilean [[boxing|boxer]]. He competed in the [[Boxing at the 1948 Summer Olympics \u2013 Heavyweight|men's heavyweight]] event at the [[1948 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=\"SportsRef\">{{cite Sports-Reference |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/bi/victor-bignon-1.html |title=V\u00edctor Bignon Olympic Results |accessdate=13 November 2018}}</ref> At the 1948 Summer Olympics, he lost to [[Adam Faul]] of Canada.<ref name=\"SportsRef\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bignon, Victor}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing]]\n[[Category:Possibly living people]]\n[[Category:Chilean male boxers]]\n[[Category:Olympic boxers of Chile]]\n[[Category:Boxers at the 1948 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games medalists in boxing]]\n\n\n{{Chile-boxing-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Chilean boxer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name           = V\u00edctor Bignon\n| full_name      = \n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| nationality    = Chilean\n| sport          = [[Boxing]]\n| birth_date     = \n| birth_place    = \n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n}}\n\n'''V\u00edctor Bignon''' was a Chilean [[boxing|boxer]]. He competed in the [[Boxing at the 1948 Summer Olympics \u2013 Heavyweight|men's heavyweight]] event at the [[1948 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=\"SportsRef\">{{cite Sports-Reference |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/bi/victor-bignon-1.html |title=V\u00edctor Bignon Olympic Results |accessdate=13 November 2018}}</ref> At the 1948 Summer Olympics, he lost to [[Adam Faul]] of Canada.<ref name=\"SportsRef\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bignon, Victor}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing]]\n[[Category:Possibly living people]]\n[[Category:Chilean male boxers]]\n[[Category:Olympic boxers of Chile]]\n[[Category:Boxers at the 1948 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing]]\n{{Chile-boxing-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Jevansen", "label": "safe", "comment": "addedCategory:Pan American Games medalists in boxing", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/V%C3%ADctor_Bignon"}
{"title_page": "Vince Shomo", "text_new": "{{short description|American boxer}}\n'''Vincent O'Neal Shomo'''<ref>[https://234fight.com/boxers-from-the-past/vince-shomo-boxer-wiki-profile/ 234fight.com: Vince Shomo]</ref> better known as '''Vince Shomo''' or '''Vincent Shomo''' (born in [[New York City|New York]], NY on 30 July 1940) is a 5' 7\" (170 cm) American amateur light welterweight boxer and champion.<ref name=boxrec>[https://boxrec.com/en/proboxer/25086 BoxRec.com: Vince Shomo]</ref>\n\nShomo won four ''Daily News'' Golden Gloves titles in five years between 1956 and 1960. In 1956 he won the sub-novice championship at 126 pounds<ref name=nydn>{{cite news|url=https://www.nydailynews.com/sports/more-sports/daily-news-golden-gloves-hall-fame-vince-shomo-article-1.1757435|author=Stephen Lorenzo|title=Daily News Golden Gloves Hall of Fame: Vince Shomo|publisher=New York Daily News|date=16 April 2014|accessdate=17 February 2020}}</ref> and three times in the 135-pound open titles in [[List of United States national amateur boxing light welterweight champions|1957, 1958 and 1960]].<ref name=nydn/><ref>[http://www.sportenote.com/vedi_dettagli.asp?id=56351 Sportenote: Record details - Vince Shomo]</ref> by taking part in a number of championship tournaments run by the National [[Amateur Boxing]] [[Welterweight]] Association also known as [[United States Amateur Champions|United States Amateur Championships]].\n\nIn 1959, Shomo came first in the lightweight category for the [[Pan-American Games]] that were organized in [[Chicago]] between 27 August and 7 September 1959. In the quarter-finals of the Pan-American Games, he defeated the representative of Brazil Jorge Sacom\u00e3na. In the semi-final duel, Shomo faced Mexico's representative [[Humberto Dip]], with whom he won by technical knockout in the first round. In the final he faced the Argentine Luis Aranda, defeating him by a technical knockout in the first round.<ref>[http://amateur-boxing.strefa.pl/Championships/PanamericanGames1959.html 3.Panamerican Games - Chicago, USA - August 27 - September 7 1959]</ref>\n\nHe continued boxing until 1968<ref name=boxrec/> with the period 1960 to 1968 as a professional boxer. Later on in the 1980s, he returned as a boxing official.<ref name=nydn/> He was conducted to the Daily News Golden Gloves Hall of Fame.<ref name=nydn/> Retired, he now lives in [[Stroudsburg, Pennsylvania|Stroudsburg]], [[Pennsylvania]], USA.\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of United States national amateur boxing light welterweight champions]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shomo, Vince}}\n[[Category:American boxers]]\n[[Category:1940 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from New York City]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games medalists in boxing]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American boxer}}\n'''Vincent O'Neal Shomo'''<ref>[https://234fight.com/boxers-from-the-past/vince-shomo-boxer-wiki-profile/ 234fight.com: Vince Shomo]</ref> better known as '''Vince Shomo''' or '''Vincent Shomo''' (born in [[New York City|New York]], NY on 30 July 1940) is a 5' 7\" (170 cm) American amateur light welterweight boxer and champion.<ref name=boxrec>[https://boxrec.com/en/proboxer/25086 BoxRec.com: Vince Shomo]</ref>\n\nShomo won four ''Daily News'' Golden Gloves titles in five years between 1956 and 1960. In 1956 he won the sub-novice championship at 126 pounds<ref name=nydn>{{cite news|url=https://www.nydailynews.com/sports/more-sports/daily-news-golden-gloves-hall-fame-vince-shomo-article-1.1757435|author=Stephen Lorenzo|title=Daily News Golden Gloves Hall of Fame: Vince Shomo|publisher=New York Daily News|date=16 April 2014|accessdate=17 February 2020}}</ref> and three times in the 135-pound open titles in [[List of United States national amateur boxing light welterweight champions|1957, 1958 and 1960]].<ref name=nydn/><ref>[http://www.sportenote.com/vedi_dettagli.asp?id=56351 Sportenote: Record details - Vince Shomo]</ref> by taking part in a number of championship tournaments run by the National [[Amateur Boxing]] [[Welterweight]] Association also known as [[United States Amateur Champions|United States Amateur Championships]].\n\nIn 1959, Shomo came first in the lightweight category for the [[Pan-American Games]] that were organized in [[Chicago]] between 27 August and 7 September 1959. In the quarter-finals of the Pan-American Games, he defeated the representative of Brazil Jorge Sacom\u00e3na. In the semi-final duel, Shomo faced Mexico's representative [[Humberto Dip]], with whom he won by technical knockout in the first round. In the final he faced the Argentine Luis Aranda, defeating him by a technical knockout in the first round.<ref>[http://amateur-boxing.strefa.pl/Championships/PanamericanGames1959.html 3.Panamerican Games - Chicago, USA - August 27 - September 7 1959]</ref>\n\nHe continued boxing until 1968<ref name=boxrec/> with the period 1960 to 1968 as a professional boxer. Later on in the 1980s, he returned as a boxing official.<ref name=nydn/> He was conducted to the Daily News Golden Gloves Hall of Fame.<ref name=nydn/> Retired, he now lives in [[Stroudsburg, Pennsylvania|Stroudsburg]], [[Pennsylvania]], USA. \n\n==See also==\n*[[List of United States national amateur boxing light welterweight champions]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shomo, Vince}}\n\n[[Category:American boxers]]\n[[Category:1940 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from New York City]]\n", "name_user": "Jevansen", "label": "safe", "comment": "addedCategory:Pan American Games medalists in boxing", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vince_Shomo"}
{"title_page": "Sean Black", "text_new": "{{short description|Jamaican boxer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name           = Sean Black\n| full_name      = \n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| nationality    = Jamaican\n| sport          = [[Boxing]]\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1970|11|13|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = \n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n}}\n\n'''Sean Black''' (born 13 November 1970) is a Jamaican [[boxing|boxer]]. He competed in the [[Boxing at the 1996 Summer Olympics \u2013 Light middleweight|men's light middleweight]] event at the [[1996 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=\"SportsRef\">{{cite Sports-Reference |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/bl/sean-black-1.html |title=Sean Black Olympic Results |accessdate=16 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Black, Sean}}\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Jamaican male boxers]]\n[[Category:Olympic boxers of Jamaica]]\n[[Category:Boxers at the 1996 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games medalists in boxing]]\n\n\n{{Jamaica-boxing-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Jamaican boxer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name           = Sean Black\n| full_name      = \n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| nationality    = Jamaican\n| sport          = [[Boxing]]\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1970|11|13|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = \n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n}}\n\n'''Sean Black''' (born 13 November 1970) is a Jamaican [[boxing|boxer]]. He competed in the [[Boxing at the 1996 Summer Olympics \u2013 Light middleweight|men's light middleweight]] event at the [[1996 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=\"SportsRef\">{{cite Sports-Reference |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/bl/sean-black-1.html |title=Sean Black Olympic Results |accessdate=16 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Black, Sean}}\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Jamaican male boxers]]\n[[Category:Olympic boxers of Jamaica]]\n[[Category:Boxers at the 1996 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n{{Jamaica-boxing-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Jevansen", "label": "safe", "comment": "addedCategory:Pan American Games medalists in boxing", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sean_Black"}
{"title_page": "Derrick Childs", "text_new": "{{Infobox Christian leader\n| type             = Archbishop \n| honorific-prefix = [[The Most Reverend]]\n| name             = Derrick Childs\n| honorific-suffix = \n| title            = [[Archbishop of Wales]]\n| image            = \n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| church           = [[Church in Wales]]\n| archdiocese      = \n| province         = \n| metropolis       = \n| diocese          = \n| see              = \n| elected          = \n| appointed        = 1983\n| term             = 1983-1986\n| term_start       = \n| quashed          = \n| term_end         = \n| predecessor      = [[Gwilym Williams]]\n| opposed          = \n| successor        = [[George Noakes]]\n| other_post       = \n<!---------- Orders ---------->\n| ordination       = \n| ordinated_by     = \n| consecration     = 1970\n| consecrated_by   = \n| cardinal         = \n| rank             = \n<!---------- Personal details ---------->\n| birth_name       = \n| birth_date       = {{Birth date|1918|01|14}}\n| birth_place      = <!-- City, administrative region, sovereign state (per [[Template:Infobox person]]) -->\n| death_date       = {{Death date and age|1987|03|18|1918|01|14}}\n| death_place      = <!-- as birth_place -->\n| buried           = \n| nationality      = \n| religion         = \n| residence        = \n| parents          = \n| spouse           = \n| children         = \n| occupation       = \n| profession       = \n| previous_post    = [[Bishop of Monmouth]] (1970-1986)\n| alma_mater       = \n| motto            = \n| signature        = \n| signature_alt    = \n| coat_of_arms     = \n| coat_of_arms_alt = \n<!---------- Sainthood ---------->\n| feast_day        = \n| venerated        = \n| saint_title      = \n| beatified_date   = \n| beatified_place  = \n| beatified_by     = \n| canonized_date   = \n| canonized_place  = \n| canonized_by     = \n| attributes       = \n| patronage        = \n| shrine           = \n| suppressed_date  = \n<!---------- Other ---------->\n| other            = \n}}\n'''Derrick Greenslade Childs''' (14 January 1918 \u2013 18 March 1987 <ref>[[Who's Who|\u201cWho was Who\u201d 1897-2007]] London, [[A & C Black]], 2007  {{ISBN|978-0-19-954087-7}}</ref>) was the Anglican [[Bishop of Monmouth]] and  [[Archbishop of Wales]].\n\nChilds grew up in [[Laugharne|Laugharne.]]<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=|title=Most Rev Derrick Childs|date=18 March 1987|work=The Times|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>  He was educated at Whitland Grammar School, before reading history at [[University College, Cardiff]]<ref name=\":0\" />[[University College, Cardiff|.]] He studied theology at [[Sarum College|Salisbury Theological College]], before being [[ordained]] in 1942.<ref>[[Crockford's Clerical Directory]]1947-48 Oxford, [[OUP]],1947</ref> He was a curate in [[Milford Haven]] and then [[Laugharne|Laugharne.]]  In 1947 he became editor of ''Cymry'r Groes,'' a magazine to serve the official youth organization of the Church of Wales<ref name=\":0\" />.  It was renamed ''Province'' in 1949; Childs remained its editor until 1967.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nChilds became [[wikt:warden|Warden]] of Llandaff House, [[Penarth]] in 1951; this was a university hall of residence provided by the diocese<ref name=\":0\" />. Four years later he became secretary of the provincial council for education and then, in 1956, secretary and treasurer of the Historical Society of the Church in Wales.<ref name=\":0\" /> In 1961 he left Llandaff House to become first director of the [[Church in Wales]] Publications.<ref name=\":0\" /> In  1965he became chancellor of [[Llandaff Cathedral]] and then [[Principal (academia)|principal]] of [[Trinity College, Carmarthen]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>[http://www.churchinwales.org.uk/monmouth/people/cathedral/BishopChilds.html Diocese of Monmouth] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110607011453/http://www.churchinwales.org.uk/monmouth/people/cathedral/BishopChilds.html |date=2011-06-07 }}</ref> At that time church colleges were fighting for their survival; Childs had an important role in ensuring that Trinity College both survived and embarked on a period of imaginative development<ref name=\":0\" />.  In 1972, he was elected bishop of Monmouth and in 1983 became [[primate (bishop)|Primate]] of the [[Church in Wales]].<ref>[[The Times]], 10 February 1983; pg. 12; Issue 61453; col F '' News in Brief ''</ref>  Childs was a [[Prelate|sub-prelate]] of the [[Venerable Order of Saint John|Order of St John of Jerusalem]]. \n\nChilds retired in 1986<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://monmouth.churchinwales.org.uk/old-pages/people/bishop/previous-bishops/bishopchilds/|title=Derrick Greenslade Childs|last=Wales|first=The Church in|website=The Diocese of Monmouth|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>. He died shortly after retirement as the result of a motor accident<ref name=\":1\" />.\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-rel|wa}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Eryl Stephen Thomas]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Bishop of Monmouth]]|years=1970\u20131986}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Royston Clifford Wright]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Gwilym Williams]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Archbishop of Wales]]|years=1983\u20131986}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[George Noakes]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Bishops of Monmouth}}\n{{Archbishops of Wales}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Childs, Derrick Greenslade}}\n[[Category:1918 births]]\n[[Category:1987 deaths]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Cardiff University]]\n[[Category:Bishops of Monmouth]]\n[[Category:Archbishops of Wales]]\n[[Category:20th-century Anglican bishops]]\n[[Category:20th-century Anglican archbishops]]\n[[Category:Sub-Prelates of the Venerable Order of Saint John]]\n\n\n{{Anglican-bishop-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Christian leader\n| type             = Archbishop \n| honorific-prefix = [[The Most Reverend]]\n| name             = Derrick Childs\n| honorific-suffix = \n| title            = [[Archbishop of Wales]]\n| image            = \n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| church           = [[Church in Wales]]\n| archdiocese      = \n| province         = \n| metropolis       = \n| diocese          = \n| see              = \n| elected          = \n| appointed        = 1983\n| term             = 1983-1986\n| term_start       = \n| quashed          = \n| term_end         = \n| predecessor      = [[Gwilym Williams]]\n| opposed          = \n| successor        = [[George Noakes]]\n| other_post       = \n<!---------- Orders ---------->\n| ordination       = \n| ordinated_by     = \n| consecration     = 1970\n| consecrated_by   = \n| cardinal         = \n| rank             = \n<!---------- Personal details ---------->\n| birth_name       = \n| birth_date       = {{Birth date|1918|01|14}}\n| birth_place      = <!-- City, administrative region, sovereign state (per [[Template:Infobox person]]) -->\n| death_date       = {{Death date and age|1987|03|18|1918|01|14}}\n| death_place      = <!-- as birth_place -->\n| buried           = \n| nationality      = \n| religion         = \n| residence        = \n| parents          = \n| spouse           = \n| children         = \n| occupation       = \n| profession       = \n| previous_post    = [[Bishop of Monmouth]] (1970-1986)\n| alma_mater       = \n| motto            = \n| signature        = \n| signature_alt    = \n| coat_of_arms     = \n| coat_of_arms_alt = \n<!---------- Sainthood ---------->\n| feast_day        = \n| venerated        = \n| saint_title      = \n| beatified_date   = \n| beatified_place  = \n| beatified_by     = \n| canonized_date   = \n| canonized_place  = \n| canonized_by     = \n| attributes       = \n| patronage        = \n| shrine           = \n| suppressed_date  = \n<!---------- Other ---------->\n| other            = \n}}\n'''Derrick Greenslade Childs''' (14 January 1918 \u2013 18 March 1987 <ref>[[Who's Who|\u201cWho was Who\u201d 1897-2007]] London, [[A & C Black]], 2007  {{ISBN|978-0-19-954087-7}}</ref>) was the Anglican [[Bishop of Monmouth]] and  [[Archbishop of Wales]].\n\nChilds grew up in [[Laugharne|Laugharne.]]<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=|title=Most Rev Derrick Childs|date=18 March 1987|work=The Times|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>  He was educated at Whitland Grammar School, before reading history at [[University College, Cardiff]]<ref name=\":0\" />[[University College, Cardiff|.]] He studied theology at [[Sarum College|Salisbury Theological College]], before being [[ordained]] in 1942.<ref>[[Crockford's Clerical Directory]]1947-48 Oxford, [[OUP]],1947</ref> He was a curate in [[Milford Haven]] and then [[Laugharne|Laugharne.]]  In 1947 he became editor of ''Cymry'r Groes,'' a magazine to serve the official youth organization of the Church of Wales<ref name=\":0\" />.  It was renamed ''Province'' in 1949; Childs remained its editor until 1967.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nChilds became [[wikt:warden|Warden]] of Llandaff House, [[Penarth]] in 1951; this was a university hall of residence provided by the diocese<ref name=\":0\" />. Four years later he became secretary of the provincial council for education and then, in 1956, secretary and treasurer of the Historical Society of the Church in Wales.<ref name=\":0\" /> In 1961 he left Llandaff House to become first director of the [[Church in Wales]] Publications.<ref name=\":0\" /> In  1965he became chancellor of [[Llandaff Cathedral]] and then [[Principal (academia)|principal]] of [[Trinity College, Carmarthen]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>[http://www.churchinwales.org.uk/monmouth/people/cathedral/BishopChilds.html Diocese of Monmouth] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110607011453/http://www.churchinwales.org.uk/monmouth/people/cathedral/BishopChilds.html |date=2011-06-07 }}</ref> In 1970, he was ordained to the [[episcopate]] and in 1983 became [[primate (bishop)|Primate]] of the [[Church in Wales]].<ref>[[The Times]], 10 February 1983; pg. 12; Issue 61453; col F '' News in Brief ''</ref>  Childs was a [[Prelate|sub-prelate]] of the [[Venerable Order of Saint John|Order of St John of Jerusalem]]. He died shortly after retirement.\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-rel|wa}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Eryl Stephen Thomas]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Bishop of Monmouth]]|years=1970\u20131986}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Royston Clifford Wright]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Gwilym Williams]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Archbishop of Wales]]|years=1983\u20131986}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[George Noakes]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Bishops of Monmouth}}\n{{Archbishops of Wales}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Childs, Derrick Greenslade}}\n[[Category:1918 births]]\n[[Category:1987 deaths]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Cardiff University]]\n[[Category:Bishops of Monmouth]]\n[[Category:Archbishops of Wales]]\n[[Category:20th-century Anglican bishops]]\n[[Category:20th-century Anglican archbishops]]\n[[Category:Sub-Prelates of the Venerable Order of Saint John]]\n\n\n{{Anglican-bishop-stub}}\n", "name_user": "RuthGooding", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Derrick_Childs"}
